{"title": "Over 60 Jamaican schoolkids hospitalised after eating cannabis rainbow candy", "tags": "world", "timestamp": "2023-10-04", "content": "KINGSTON \u2013 More than 60 Jamaican primary school pupils were hospitalised after eating potent rainbow-coloured cannabis candy, the Caribbean country\u2019s education minister said on social media platform X.\nThe candy caused them to vomit and hallucinate.\n\u201cI feel confident that together, we will strengthen our safety and security regime to combat the unconscionable sale of marijuana-infused products to children,\u201d Ms Fayval Williams said on Tuesday, noting the \u201cmost unfortunate\u201d circumstances under which she met parents and stakeholders of Ocho Rios Primary School.\nLate on Monday, Ms Williams had shared an image she said had been reported to her ministry showing a colourful packet of \u201cfull-throttle rainbow sour belts\u201d, each containing 100mg of THC, a substance found in marijuana \u2013 which is considered a strong dose for experienced adults.\n\u201cOne little boy said he only had one sweetie,\u201d Ms Williams said, adding several of the schoolchildren had been given intravenous drips to speed up recovery. \u201cThat\u2019s how potent this product is.\u201d\nJamaica decriminalised possession of up to 57g of marijuana for religious, medicinal and scientific purposes in 2015, and set up a licensing agency for the country\u2019s legal medical cannabis industry.\nRadio Jamaica reported that the Ganja Growers and Producers Association of Jamaica was suggesting a public education programme for responsible consumption by adults and to prevent consumption by children, as well as pushing for more packaging regulations. REUTERS"}